eld, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"en":{"about 1350–":"about 1350–Deceased","1350–Female":"1350–Deceased","1387–1468":"1387–1468","1350–Male":"1350–Deceased","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","about 1350":"about 1350","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wellinge","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Shropshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Welling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Welling","meanings":["English: habitational name from Welwyn (Hertfordshire) or Welling in Bexley (Kent), with a suspicion of an alternative unidentified source. The Hertfordshire placename means ‘at the willow trees’, from Old English <i>wel(i)gum</i>, dative plural form of <i>welig</i> ‘willow’. The Kent placename may derive from Old English <i>wella</i> ‘well, spring, stream’ + the placename forming suffix <i>-ing</i>. In some cases this name may represent a development of   Llewellyn  , particularly near the Welsh border.","German: habitational name from any of various places in the Rhineland called Welling or Wellingen."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705197,"age":105,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"William Wellinge was born about 1350, in England. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1387–1468":"1387–1468","1350–Male":"1350–Surnud","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1350–":"noin 1350–Kuollut","1350–Female":"1350–Kuollut","1387–1468":"1387–1468","1350–Male":"1350–Kuollut","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","about 1350":"noin 1350","Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England":"Little Waldingfield, Suffolk, England","England":"England"},"fr":{"about 1350–":"environ 1350–Décédé","1350–Female":"1350–Décédée","1387–1468":"1387–1468","1350–Male":"1350–Décédé","1468":"1468","1455":"1455","1387":"1387","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","about 1350":"environ 13